  "text": "H10 cells are derived from NRCM, but are altered by the immortalization. Therefore, we performed a similar coexpression of G␣ s with either G␤ 1 WT␥ 2 or G␤ 1 H266L␥ 2 in freshly isolated NRCM and determined the cAMP accumulation in the presence of propranolol. Note that NRCM are more sensitive to adenoviral infection than H10 cells. Thus, for similar effective adenoviral infections a 10-fold reduced MOI was sufficient ( Figure 3A ). Overexpression of G␤ 1 WT␥ 2 did not alter basal cAMP compared with GFP controls (GFP: 60.7Ϯ7 pmol/mg; G␤ 1 WT␥ 2 : 57.7Ϯ10 pmol/mg). In NRCM, we observed two effects of G␤␥ overexpression on cAMP formation: (1) when compared with the expression of G␣ s alone ( Figure 3B ), coexpression of G␣ s and G␤␥ dimers resulted in a strong reduction (89Ϯ3%) in basal cAMP synthesis, which is because of the well known formation of inactive G␣ s ␤␥ heterotrimers (see Figure  1B ) in the absence of a stimulated receptor [CITATION_1] ; and (2) beyond this expected effect, overexpression of G␤ 1 H266L␥ 2 induced a further significant suppression of the receptor-independent cAMP synthesis. Similarly to NDPKϩ cells, cAMP levels of G␤ 1 H266L␥ 2 myocytes were reduced by 30% to 50% compared with G␤ 1 WT␥ 2 myocytes in a G␣ s level dependent manner ( Figure 3C ).",
